    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-04T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-04T04:00:00-05:00" n="574"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d574">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.6211/315: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-04T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >January 4, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 4—9:26
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>13. My telegram 1113, December 20, [1939,] noon.<note n="65" xml:id="d574fn65">
                        <ref target="frus1939v01#pg_498">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., p. 498</ref>.</note> A member of the staff
                    of the German Embassy has informed me in strict confidence that the discussions
                    now in progress between the German economic delegation and the Soviet
                    authorities have resulted in an agreement by the Soviets to supply Germany
                    during 1940 with 500,000 metric tons of apatite. The negotiations are still
                    proceeding with respect to manganese. I understand the quantity under
                    consideration is also about 500,000 tons for 1940. Deliveries of the oil and
                    fodder previously agreed upon are under way. Ritter<note n="66"
                        xml:id="d574fn66">Karl Ritter, Ambassador on special assignment in the
                        German Foreign Office, in charge of economic warfare questions.</note> left
                    Moscow for Berlin last night. Schnurre<note n="67" xml:id="d574fn67">Karl
                        Schnurre, Head of the Eastern European and Baltic Section of the Commercial
                        Policy Division of the German Foreign Office.</note> and the other members
                    of the delegation are remaining.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
